comment.undefined: Function objects are used to model the decomposition of the structure of a process.
A connector determines the behavior of the process in case its control ?ow is split up into or joined from several execution branches.
A transaction in SAP is described as a screen. Here, they represent the actions undertaken in the application SAP to perform a function in a process flow.
Item external to a system (such as a process) that is transformed by the system (usually together with one or more other items) to become an output.

comment.en: In IndustryPrint 5, function objects are used to model the decomposition of a process.

comment.undefined: An application system type classifies individual application systems which have exactly the same technological properties. Process steps might be supported by application systems. Object describe IT systems (library for IT systems available).
Human being that puts effort in the processing of a process step (function). It belongs to the organizational unit that is responsible for the specific process step.

A Value-Added Chain is a process that represents an element of the process chain. A process hierarchy can be realized by hierarchically structuring value chains, thus modeling business areas, process groups, business processes and business process variants using the sam notation.
House: represents enabler processes.
Rule element that unites the control flow after being split into several branches. Has several incoming paths (at least two) and one outgoing.
A Business Process Landscape (BP_Landscape) is a detailed overview of a specific Core- or Enabler Process.

comment.en: The lowest level of detail, a task are the activities required to execute a subprocess. A single task within a subprocess can be manual or system supported. E.g. Create Purchase Order

comment.undefined: The connector is responsible for splitting the control flow in at least two different branches, which are executed parallely where all branches must be followed.
The function type represents several action elements as task, process interfaces or business process activities.
Rule element that splits the control flow into several branches. Has one incoming path and several (at least two) outgoing paths.

A set of core and enabler processes of Infineon on Level 0 (highest level). This level helps helps organizing project work/ development and represents a single track in the oneSAP project. It is based on a Deloitte standard which was adapted to Infineon's needs.
The amount of energy, work, goods, or services produced by a machine, factory, company, or an individual in a period.
A set of a processes covering a single business area. Usually under the ownership of one business process owner and aligning with a function.
It is responsible for splitting the control flow up in at least two different branches, due to an nonexclusive choice where one or several branches can be followed.

comment.en: Set up with connection to a function or activity or VAC. It can be either input or output, where the direction of the arrow describes whether it is an input or an output. Set up of a connection is not mandatory.

comment.undefined: Collection of other services used as input to a production process or which are created during a production process.
IPF is the structured overview of all IFX Core and Enabler Processes. It contains 4 Core Processes and 6 Enabler Processes.

comment.en: Denotes the event that stands at the beginning of a branch in the process flow and thus, triggers the execution of this branch or the total process.

comment.undefined:
One and only one of the incoming pathways is required to proceed along the flow
One and only one of the outgoing pathways can be taken
Divide should be made with yes/no question and lines labelled only with ?yes? or ?no?
Gateway must therefore be named with this Yes/No question
Physical equipment that makes up a computer system, such as circuit boards, keyboard and mouse, monitor, printer, power supply, storage devices. Contrasts with software.
Semi or fully automated device that magnifies human physical and/or mental capabilities in performing one or more operations.

comment.en: Function objects are used to model the decomposition of the process flow.

The event is a passive element since it represents a change of state but does not cause it. Furthermore it can characterize the conditions and the results of an activity, which in turn triggers the next function. An event with no incoming arc is called start event, while an event with no outgoing arc is called end event.

comment.undefined: Represents an object in the EPC model. Includes all elements used in the modelling procedure of an EPC diagram.

comment.en:
Process interfaces connect several process models on the same process hierarchical level by linking the EPCs according to their shared events (also known as "horizontal navigation"). They thus facilitate process structuring and navigation by keeping models concise and easy-to-read.
Functionality: Jump function to next process (e.g. EPC, VAC), typically at the end of process branches. In the EPC flow there is an Event directly before.

comment.undefined: A Business Process (BP) consists of a series of value-creating activities that reach the performance expected by customers and fulfill goals derived from the business strategy.

comment.en:
An EPC describes a Business Process Flow, which is a sequence of required tasks to create specified outputs using defined inputs.
A Business Process Flow is a sequence of required tasks to create specified outputs using defined inputs.

comment.undefined: A set of a processes covering a single business area. Usually under the ownership of one business process owner and correlates to one module. E.g. Procurement
Object to describe the role. Type of responsibility is defined by the linkage between function or activity and role. IFX options: carries out, contribute, must be informed.
A set of process types and related process groups that define the enterprise for a particular industry/sector.

comment.en: Denotes the output element of a function in the process flow.

comment.undefined: The matter from which something can be made. Material can include but is not limited to raw and processed material, components, parts, assemblies, sub-assemblies, fuels, lubricants, coolants, cleaning agents, and small tools and accessories that may be consumed directly or indirectly.
To graphically depict functional and process decomposition, function objects are diagramed on models in IndustryPrint 5.
A collection of subprocesses that meet a specific business objective. E.g. Perform Sourcing or Purchase Materials and Services
The first level of process decomposition that is comprised of subprocesses that depict a business objective.

comment.en: Denotes the input element to a function in the process flow.

comment.undefined: A Business Process (BP) Activity is a part of a Business Process containing one or more sub Business Processes or a Process Flow.

comment.en: Additional information to a process like work schedule, production plans, etc.

comment.undefined: Rules allow to model alternative, exclusive alternative and parallel process flows.
A grouping of related tasks that create an output within the larger objective of the subprocess. E.g. Create and Maintain Purchase Orders
The second and lowest level of process decomposition that is comprised of tasks that depict the role-based activities of the subprocess.

comment.en: Denotes the event element that stands at the end of a branch in the process flow and thus, ends the process flow branch or the total process.

comment.undefined: Represents the inverse property of activatesTask.
The result of a function in a process flow is controlled by a goal.
Software is executed by a function in a process flow.
A process step creates an event. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.

comment.en: States whether someone is responsible for the SubprocessDiagram or not.

comment.undefined: A process step is activated by an event or a rule. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
A process step is supported by an Application system.
A rule is assigned to a process step. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
A rule leads to an event. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
Physical or non-physical output is produced by a function in a process flow.
A process step can have technical term(s) as output.

comment.en: Description of all requirements for the certain input or output.

comment.undefined: A goal controls the outcome of a function in a process flow.
An EPC can have another EPC following which is dependent on the result. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in a VACD.

comment.en: Represents the connections and dependencies between models

comment.undefined: A function in a process flow transforms environmental data like work schedules.
A function in a process flow excutes software.
An event is dependent on a rule. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
Represents the inverse property of represents.
The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC, where an Event or a Rule activate a Task or Process Interface.
A aris:BPActivity is the graphical representation of a aris:VACD or aris:BPFlow in a aris:VACD.
Role(s) to be informed after/ during the process step is carried out (one-way-communication) (equivalent to I in RACI notation)

comment.en: Describes the experience that is required.

comment.undefined: A process step is carried out by role(s) or organizational unit(s) (equivalent to R in RACI notation).
A function in a process flow uses external resources like machines or computer hardware during its execution.
The execution of a function in a process flow is under the responsibility of an organizational unit.

comment.en: Links a Model with the elements represented by it.

comment.undefined: An external physical or non-physical input is used in a function in a process flow and is therefore input of it.
Value-added chain diagrams have value-added chain diagrams as subordinates. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
A process step follows a process step. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
EPCs have value-added chain diagrams as superior. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
The connector is used to represent the chronological order of value chain elements.

comment.en: Represents the unique identifier of the element.

comment.undefined: Represents the inverse property of activatesFunction.

comment.en: Links a FuncitonObject or a ModelElement with the Model that it's represented in.

comment.undefined: An event is created by a process step. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
An EPC can have another EPC previous to itself and is dependent on its results. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in a VACD.
A software independent business object or product/services may be input for a process step.
Specialization of the activates property that links the class Rule with Task in the course of the process flow.
Value-added chain diagrams have another value-added chain diagram as superior. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
EPCs and Value-added chain diagrams consist of objects.
The execution of a function in a process flow is processed by a person (human output).

comment.en: Represents the owner of a business process (flow).
Contains the transaction code assigned to a Screen in SAP.

comment.undefined: An external resource is used by a function in a process flow.
Environmental data is transformed by a function in a process flow.
A rule evaluates an event. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
An organizational unit is responible for a function in a process flow.
A process step can have technical term(s) as input.
Denotes the connection between a "Function" and another "Process" as this process may deliver an output used in this function.

comment.en: Describes the knowledge that is required.

comment.undefined: A process step is worked on by collaboration of role(s).
An object is relevant for EPCs and value-added chain diagrams.
A process step leads to a rule. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.
Denotes to which instance of "Process" an instance of a "Process Element" belongs.
Role(s) or Organizational unit(s) that carrries (carry) out the process step (equivalent to R in RACI notation)
Specialization of the activates property that links the class Event with Task and Process Interface in the course of the process flow.
EPCs can have other EPCs as superiors. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
Some person, referred to as human output here, processes a function in a process flow.

comment.en: Describes the mission or goal of a business process (flow).

comment.undefined: An event is evaluated by a rule. The connector is used to represent the chronological order in an EPC.

comment.en: Describes the requirements for the specific handling of objects.

comment.undefined: Role(s) that contribute(s) to a process step during it is carried out.

comment.en: Denotes the scope of a specific business process (flow).

comment.undefined: Value-added chain diagrams have EPCs as subordinates. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
A process step is supported by an application system type.
A result of a process step is forwarded to role(s).

comment.en: Denotes a remark or an example that is given specific to an element.

comment.undefined: Enables the modelling of the process flow by logically connecting the different process elements. Therefore, the domain and the range are set to a "Process Element".
EPCs can have other EPCs as subordinates. The connector is used to represent the hierarchical order.
